     <br>

    <h4><strong>Longer version</strong></h4>

<p>A while ago at a Rails Girls event I asked my coach about creating this and she said that is wasn’t possible as each show would have_many theatres and each theatre would have_many shows. After reading a couple of documents about has_many_through, I thought I’d give it a crack. I had to work out what the ‘through’ element would be and settled on ‘performances’.</p>

<p>Obviously there would need to be a Show model, which would take a name attribute and a Theatre model which would need the name of the theatre along with the address so that I could look it up on Google Maps. Each show and theatre would have_many performances. Ooh, and performances would need to have a date as well.</p>

<p>I decided to create all of the views to start with just in case I discovered I needed them later. I could always delete them if I didn’t.</p>

<p>So I set off scaffolding and created shows and theatres. Easy. But then it came to creating the performances one and I couldn’t for the life of me figure out how to set up the relationships with the show and theatre models. I tried a couple of things using migrations but they ended up not working. So I deleted everything and started again, changing the name of the app to ‘theatres’. Bad move. Turns out you can’t have a model with the same name as the app. So ANOTHER start. And it still isn’t working.</p>

<p>Right, I’m obviously going to have to write the damn thing from scratch. So I got to work.</p>
  
